04413nam a22006255i 9780292767447DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212015txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927674477 a10.7560/7608062doi  a(DE-B1597)588436  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aDS153.3b.C68 2014eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a933/.52231 aCorbett, Elena, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCompetitive Archaeology in Jordan :bNarrating Identity from the Ottomans to the Hashemites /cElena Corbett. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliterations -- tCHAPTER 1 Archaeology Is Politics: The Meaning of Archaeological Heritage in Jordan -- tCHAPTER 2 Holy Land Core and Periphery -- tCHAPTER 3 Antiquity and Modernity in Southeastern Bilad al-Sham -- tCHAPTER 4 British Mandate: Core, Periphery, and Ownership of Narrative -- tCHAPTER 5 Antiquities of a Hashemite State in Mandatory Space -- tCHAPTER 6 Antiquity, Pan-National, and Nation-State Narratives in the Expanded Hashemite Kingdom -- tCHAPTER 7 Return to the Core -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn examination of archaeology in Jordan and Palestine, Competitive Archaeology in Jordan explores how antiquities have been used to build narratives and national identities. Tracing Jordanian history, and the importance of Jerusalem within that history, Corbett analyzes how both foreign and indigenous powers have engaged in a competition over ownership of antiquities and the power to craft history and geography based on archaeological artifacts. She begins with the Ottoman and British Empires—under whose rule the institutions and borders of modern Jordan began to take shape—asking how they used antiquities in varying ways to advance their imperial projects. Corbett continues through the Mandate era and the era of independence of an expanded Hashemite Kingdom, examining how the Hashemites and other factions, both within and beyond Jordan, have tried to define national identity by drawing upon antiquities. Competitive Archaeology in Jordan traces a complex history through the lens of archaeology’s power as a modern science to create and give value to spaces, artifacts, peoples, narratives, and academic disciplines. It thus considers the role of archaeology in realizing Jordan’s modernity—drawing its map; delineating sacred and secular spaces; validating taxonomies of citizens; justifying legal frameworks and institutions of state; determining logos of the nation for display on stamps, currency, and in museums; and writing history. Framing Jordan’s history in this way, Corbett illustrates the manipulation of archaeology by governments, institutions, and individuals to craft narratives, draw borders, and create national identities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aArchaeologyxPolitical aspectszJordan. 0aArchaeologyxPolitical aspectszPalestine. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/76080640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292767447423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292767447/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK